PROJECT 5: EC2 Hands-on + Security
Date: Day 8
What I built:

Launched EC2 instance (dipesh-web-server) using Amazon Linux 2023 on t2.micro free tier
Configured instance inside dipesh-security-vpc with dipesh-public-subnet
Attached existing security group dipesh-web-sg with HTTP, HTTPS and SSH rules
Created and safely stored key pair (dipesh-key-pair)
Attached IAM role with S3 read only and SSM managed instance core permissions
Connected to EC2 securely using AWS Systems Manager Session Manager
Enabled detailed monitoring on EC2 instance
Created CloudWatch alarm for CPU utilization above 80%
Connected alarm to SNS topic for automatic email alerts
Stopped instance after use to avoid charges

Security concepts applied:

Launched instance inside custom VPC not default VPC
Used existing hardened security group with least privilege rules
Attached IAM role instead of using access keys
Used SSM Session Manager instead of open SSH connection
Immediately reverted SSH rule from anywhere to My IP only
Enabled detailed monitoring for security visibility
Created CPU alarm for anomaly detection
Instance stopped when not in use to reduce attack surface

Challenges faced and resolved:

EC2 Instance Connect failed with SSH connection error
Investigated root cause — AWS Instance Connect uses different IP ranges
Identified SSM Session Manager as more secure alternative
Successfully connected via SSM with zero open ports required
SSH security group temporarily opened to 0.0.0.0/0 for troubleshooting
Immediately reverted back to My IP only after issue resolved
Documented as security lesson learned

Real world value:

SSM Session Manager is the industry standard for EC2 access in real companies
No open SSH ports means significantly reduced attack surface
CloudWatch alarms with SNS notifications is standard monitoring setup
IAM roles on EC2 is always preferred over access keys in production
Stopping unused instances is standard cost and security practice

Key learnings:

EC2 Instance Connect requires open SSH ports which is a security risk
SSM Session Manager requires zero open ports — most secure access method
IAM roles must be stopped and started to take effect on EC2
Detailed monitoring gives 1 minute intervals vs default 5 minutes
CloudWatch alarms connected to SNS provide automated incident response
Always stop EC2 instances when not in use to avoid charges
Security groups should always follow least privilege principle
